===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|首|或|c1=s|c2=p|t1=head|ls=psc}}. This character largely displaced {{och-l|聝}} in the received corpus of ancient classics. See also {{zh-m|*𢦞}}.

===Etymology===
{{rfe|zh|Against traditional glossings (e.g. {{w|Shuowen Jiezi}}'s), {{w|Cheng Hao}} ({{lw|zh|程顥}}) & {{w|Cheng Yi}} ({{lw|zh|程頤}}) propose that {{ltc-l|馘}} < (OC ''kʷrɯːɡ'') originally meant "to behead captives" (「馘, 斬獲也」); their proposal is supported by Milburn (2018).<ref>Milburn, O. (2018). "Headhunting in ancient China: The history of violence and denial of knowledge." ''Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies'', '''81(1)''', p. 103-120. doi:10.1017/S0041977X17001446</ref>}}

